Nimzovich-Larsen attack modern variation
With him advancing g3 and b3 I want to really push to control the center.
Not super excited about this position.
getting ready to protect b5. I knew he would push pawns to my knight sitting at c6 or try to lure Nxb4 Bxb7
and here it comes
I didn't know of another move to do here.
I'm starting to like how this is turning out.
Going to be a little aggresive here. If I get into trouble I can castle queen side and get out of immediate danger while I regroup.
I think better move here would be h4 temporarily halting a push of my pawns to his king.
I have a definate advantage now.
The end is almost near.

black resigns. It was just a matter of finishing the game at this point. I felt good with this game. My first tourney in the advanced section. I will not win it but can sure throw the bracket off. He was the top rated player in the bracket. I know he just under estimated me and will probably kill me in our next game. Thanks for following along.

French Defence Advanced Variation/Nimzowitsch Variation probably other names too.
(It's unfortunate that sometimes chess players are tested and 'fail' because the chess player is unable to respond with the correct chess tradition of the questioner).

I know strong players who don't use this Variation as they believe White ends up with a backwards Pawn for the rest of the game.  They'd be right until White loses the pawn of course.

After getting my head around Opening i hope to concentrate more on the Tarrasch variation 3.Nd2
Alternative 3...Bd7 4.Nf3 a6 5.c4 dxc4 6.Bxc4 Bc6 7.0-0 Be7 8.Nc3 h6 9.Qe2 Nd7 10 Rd1 with White having a slight advantage

Old traditional lines that have proved their test of time.
4. ...Ne7 5.Nf3 Nec6 6.Bd3 b6 7.Bg5 Qd7 8.0-0 Ba6 9.dxc5 bxc5 10 Bxa6 Nxa6
 11. c4 white slight advantage

I feel White is only responding to the treats of Black and as White feel on the back foot.
Black is at a crossroads 5...Nh6 6.dxc5 Bxc5 7.b4 Bb6 8.bxh6 gxh6 9.b5 Ne7 10. Bd3 Ng6 11. 0-0 0-0 12. a4 f6  with equal chances

5..Qb6 a very common move 6.Be2 cxd4 7.cxd4 Nh6 8. b3 Nf5 9.Bb2 Bb4+ 10. Kf1
While the dark-squared Bishop is out of sight move the bN as another Defender on c2 for the d4 Pawn
I was suprise dby this move I took for granted the Knight would go to f5.

few different things h5 means the Knight has to move again.
g5 is less friendly for the Black Bishop
g5 maybe an outpost for Bishop or Night.
I think this is a mistake on my part.
White missed some opportunities there and now has an isolated Pawn far from any support

White doesn't have any moves to impact on the game.
Waiting to be put down by Black.
While the exchanges relieve the tension I would hope 23....0-0 would mean Black has a comfortable game.
I suppose securing free lines for DSB Queen and Rook to follow can't be any harm.
Nusiance check.....
..... that brings the Knight back into the game
Nusinace check part 2 but credit to Black his pieces are focussed on d4 and d8
So all this blocking is to perform Castling right?

White had some thinking to do Qa4 means the Knight doesn't move but the Black is in play after 26....0-0

Also I considered Rd1 probably the Best Move shores up the defence gives King back f1.
also axb4 just because I hate passed pawns.  But Black lost a tempo by taking on b4 so it would be just be giving it back to him.  Also 26. RC1 0-0 27Qa4 bxa3 28 Bxa3+ Kf8 29.Bb5 keeps things sharp.
Is this premature?
28....0-0 or 28.....Qb6 how can White win?
from here it's forced mate.

lucky lucky lucky.

It's a reminder that if a player is leading for a long time don't take your eyes off the ball.
Also develop all your pieces.

This is the standard position of the french defence. White now has 4 main options: 3. exd5 which is the drawish and slightly boring exchange variation 3. Nc3 which is the classical variation 3. Nd2 which is the Tarrasch and lastly 3. e5 which is the advance variation.

Well here it is: The advance variation. White immediately grabs central space and tries to cramp black's game. Notably Black's g8 knight is denied its favourite square (f6) and the c8 bishop will be difficult to develop. So what does black have in return? He has a solid pawn structure a strong dark squared bishop and importantly a potential target; white's centre.
Striking at the base of white's central pawn chain is the logical continuation.
Adding further support to white's centre.
Developing whilst putting pressure on white's centre. 4. ...Qb6 has also been played to prevent 5. Be3.
Same theme again; white develops and tries to hold onto his large centre. Time to mix things up a bit...

This move looks absurd! White seems to be able to take my knight with 6. Bxh6 and leave black with doubled pawns. Well yes that's true but then I would gain several compensating advantages such as the bishop pair the ability to put my bishop quickly on the g7 square further pressuring white's centre potential f file pressure (after I play f6) and a few others. So what if White doesn't take on h6? My knight doesn't plan to stay on h6 but instead has ideas of moving in a couple of moves as we shall see.

This is a very common reply to 5. ...Qb6 so white was probably trying to stay in familiar territory by playing this move. However I am not obliged to transpose into white's opening of choice by playing 6. ...Qb6 so why should I?

! I now get my kingside involved in hammering white's centre. Note that although this move seems to weaken my kingside there is no way for white to exploit this as a check on the h5-e8 diagonal can be blocked by my knight.
White reasons that against my seemingly irregular opening that development is the key.

! My knight slots in nicely with my pawn structure and also aims at white's e5 pawn. Now white must find the correct way to defend his attacked centre as I am threatening e5 with 3 pieces and it is only defended twice.

Mistake. 8. Qe2 was also bad. The path to equality was 8. exf6! conceding part of the centre. White can't hold onto his overlarge centre and after this greedy move black causes serious dis-coordination amongst the white pieces.
! Lashing out at the bishop. The weakening of the pawn structure is unimportant in this position as white will have no time (or piece coordination) with which to take advantage of it.
9. Bg3 was more consistent with defending the centre but it has the same reply as this move.
! Driving back white's knight to a passive square. This will allow me to safely win a pawn in the centre.
This move was probably the best as the other squares were horrible places for the knight but now white will have problem's developing his queen's knight.
No reason to delay taking the pawn for any longer. Now ironically BLACK's centre will dominate whereas before it was white's central pawn chain that cramped black!
Temporarily winning back the pawn.
Taking advantage of the unfortunate position of the bishop to undouble my pawns.
Forced to give the bishop a square.
And again using the bishop to set up my formation with gain of time.
Pinning my e pawn.
Looks very strange blocking in my dark squared bishop but it is actually going to land on the h6-d2 diagonal and this move gives my queen ideas of transferring to the more active c5 square.
Now that there is no pin the bishop had to retreat.
I take my opportunity to again use the bishop to gain time for pawn advances. The threat is 16. ...h4 winning the bishop.
Creating a hole for the bishop so that it may finally come to a safe square.
Even more harassment of the bishop! Note that 18. hxg3? loses a piece to 18. ...hxg3 (threatening both the rook and bishop) 19. Rxh8 gxf2+ and followed by 20. ...Nxh8.
This bishop finally lands on a safe spot on the back rank (far from ideal). I now proceed to finally win the c5 pawn and go a pawn up.
Making use of the pin on the d pawn (the bishop on g1 pins it to my c5 queen)
And now my bishop finally hits on its ideal diagonal. Note that before this was controlled by white's bishop which now sits lazily on g1.
Setting up a blockade on my central pawns. I will remove it later when my king is out of the centre.
Perhaps trying to threaten my h4 pawn but it turns out that this move just wastes time.
! It turns out that there is no threat to h4 because if 23. Bxh4? then 23. ...Bxd2+ followed by 24. ...Rxh4 wins a piece.
Pinning my knight but it gets my king out of the centre whilst white's is unable to leave.
The obvious choice adding further pressure to my pinned knight.
I decide to improve my bishop's position before dealing with the threat.

If we now take a moment to asses the position we can see that black is clearly much better. Black's pieces take up active positions and exert a lot of central control whilst white has no good square for his dsb and his pieces also lack the space to manoeuvre effectively.
Now is the time to begin kingside operations so I bring my knight closer to the action.
A slightly dubious move. Better was 27. Bc4 to exchange away my good bishop.
Now the king tries to help out but it becomes a target.
30. Rg1 also loses to 30. ...Qh7!
And now white is almost paralysed.
Taking advantage of the pin on the c file.
Now I am threatening 33. ...Be3 winning a piece so white becomes desperate.
Now the threat to win a piece is gone but I am the exchange and a pawn up.
My thinking was that threatening to promote a pawn should win even more material.
The time is ripe to exchange off the pieces and simplify to a winning endgame.
And  now white must sacrifice further material to stop the pawn.

!? I could have taken with Bxd2 and be a rook up but then white would be free to take my e pawn and his king would be unrestricted. Now however if white doesn't take my rook then his king is stuck on the back rank and he is unable to take my e pawn. If he does then he has only simplified the game even further making the win easy.
And now a piece up I win easily.
I first centralise my king.
Bc1 was faster
Forcing white to create a hole for my king to penetrate.
Now I must play to not allow white to defend the b pawn with his king.
Everything is ready.
White can no longer defend the queenside pawns.

And white resigned as there is no way of stopping my a pawn promoting. Thanks for reading if you wish to criticize my annotation please give a short sample line as evidence as just saying "terrible move" isn't very helpful ;)
A seemingly logical pawn push by my opponent gave me a decisive advantage.  I have the black pieces.
With this unusual move I had to wonder what I was up against.
The pawn pushes on both edges look like blitz moves; black is allowed a major lead in development.
Prepares an escape square for the DSB when the d4 thrust comes.
DSB is established and safe outside the pawn chain.  White can and does push the d pawn and constrict black's position but I think I will still be OK after this.
The promised push.  Looks good for white.

The resultant constricted position.  However I think I can transfer the N to g6 and have a setup I've sometimes seen my favorite speed player in Harvard Square Raoul play countless times with two adjacent knights.

Protects the e4 pawn but constricts his DSB which flaw is about to lose him the game.  Were Bd4 or a queen move better?  White however seems to be moving toward a swift Kingside attack and this N move fits that general idea I guess.
Unsure whether it was safe I decide to castle into what might become a storm.  I believe White has good attacking possibilities but...
...this isn't one of them.  I can get three pawns for my undeveloped LSB and disrupt the White King's safety as part of the bargain.  I think this may be considered the losing move.
The fortuitous exchange sequence begins
Capturing is probably not the best move available to White given what follows.

And there it is!  The f2 pawn is attacked twice and can only be protected with the queen and King.  At this point perhaps Rh2 accepting the trade of R for N was white's best option.  Alternatively he can move the queen to avoid the threatened Q-R fork.
But this isn't the right square.  If 10. g4 isn't immediately losing this is.  The queen now must be given up to avoid mate.
Forcing a nasty choice.
Wrong choice it turns out:

The K cannot move.  The Queen is forced to capture.  If instead 13. Qxf2 at least white would have both the N and B as collateral for the lost Q; this way the B stays on the board.  Either way White is lost.
Ahead 6 points I trade whenever possible.
Now I have plenty of time and material but am far behind in development.  It is still a chess game and I must still win the won game.
I suppose I wanted to push the c pawn and open the board but this move seems less than aggressive.
Seems simple enough to parry with...
...this but later this setup will be a liability for me.
Eyeing a nice post on f5 but I have a sequence to stop that.
Forks K and P.
I am now +8 and begin playing rather sloppily as a result.
Solves the skewer but perhaps allowing the b7 pawn to fall was a quicker way to open up lines to the white king.
Poor choice on my part as the following moves prove.
OK but Q is pinned to covering the c pawn for the time being.
Now the Q is forced to protect two weak pawns.  I am taking forever to translate my material advantage into an attack.  In the meantime I am missing a tactical combination that White is threatening.
Threatening Rb1 and forcing one set of rooks off the board.
Avoiding the forced trade.
?? Pinning the N planning to double the rooks on the b file.  Seemed good at the time but here comes the start of the aforementioned combination:
! gxh6?? allows 30. Nf6! and a Royal fork.  Luckily I wake up in time to avoid the trap.
Several options work to avoid the fork; this one threatens Qf4+ and the start of an attack.  In the meantime the R on h6 is now under threat.
? White offers to trade rooks not in his best interest.  Meanwhile the K has walked into a tight spot.
Refusing the trade maintaining tension.
?? Oops.  Threatens the Q and advances on the Black King but allows mate in 1.
Cheers thanks for a good game!

The beginning of a game that will be fuill with tricks and tactics.
It start a biut slow but at it height both players throw in some big moves.
And the game seem to change direction several times.

Its only thorugh sheer agressiveness that I managed to win it in the end.
Buty more importanly my oponnent and me both trully enjoyed playing this game.

The Kings gambit I am not fond of it.
It has caused me some troubles because I am too aggressive a player to like defense.

I have successfully tried Qh4+ several times.
Unfortunately if white plays correctly he will have a good game.
Odd move and certainly not the strongest.
I my experience developing another piece is always the best mpve.

I am not liking it how to deal with that centre? 
I contemplated d5 but I did not like it.
So instead I took the safe road but it is too passive.
To slow probably.

Black now has a very cramped position but white has commited himself on the Kings side.
If I can just break it open for my pieces to come out I could do some severe damage.
But for now I will have to content developing as many pieces as I can.

I feel this is to black advantage since I am gaining a strong field on e5.
White is probably intending an assault against my king on the Queen side.
Let me make good use of that e5 square first.

Making room to manouver.
Unfortunately the Queen is now sidetracked for a large part of the game.
Perhaphs then Qe8 might have been better.
Not bad I have a good hold on e5 now.

Alright he has shown his hand he intends to assualt my king.
The pawn on g4 give me a chance to open up lines towards his own king.
But I am crammed and need space to manouver.
Aiming for e2 but here the Queen is out of action for a long time to come.
I need space! So I sacrifice a pawn hoping for open lines I can use.
I

Had I been white I would have continued with Ng3.
Both f6 and f5 are good for using as a focal point of attack.
The extra pawn is not that valuable.
AFter 20.Ng3 h5; 21 Nf5hg4; 22.hg4 Bg6 my position is not great.

Giving black some crucial open lines.
I dont think white should have taken this pawn at all.
That should be worth a pawn.

Opening even more lines. 
If my Queen were on the kings side I could have a strong attack going here.
Alas she has wandered of to far places.


You might notice the bishop aiming at the rook on a1.
Alas there seems no direct way to profit from that.

Things have changed black has good play but his Queen is still offside.
If only it was available on the Kings side of the board!

The game of tactics has started.
Its is going to be a brawl.

Ussually I would play asa agressive as possible.
I regret not playing an immediate Rh4.
But I got worried about Qf5+ and wantd to remove that first.
White needs to be carefull to take the g5 pawn since it will bring in black Queen after Qb6+
That one move delay has allowed white to build a strong defence.

To my disappointment white has had time enough to solidify his position.
If only I had not played Kb8...
That is dangerous since it allows blacks Queen to re-enter the game
Getting the most important piece into play

Nice move! 
This move makes it an interesting game by itself.
But there is more to come...

For a moment I though I just lost major material.
The I realized it is a fake sacrifice.
White is hoping to release some pressure on the h file.
Forced.

Here she is finally...
The rooks sacrifice has actually allowed black to bring in reinforcements.

How should black continue now?
I took my time deciding on my next move.

After 29..Rf2+; 3-.Bg2 there is not time to play Bxe4 because of Qd8#;
Also Nd3 seems possible but after much thinking I did not like it enough.

So how to continue?

This is a very mean move!
One of my best moves in this game.

It is hard to see its real purpose which is to capture white Queen with either Bg5 or Ng6.
Of course I had to calculate responses like Nf1 but I think black comes out on top.
White needs to be on his guard!
That is too simple Nf1 seems better.
Surpise!

I noticed Qf4 but I wanted more.
My reasoning was that this should win me two or three pawns.
So it should be h=just as good right?
What I like about Qxb3 is that is leaves all white pawns hanging.
It seemed more aggressive to play this way and I figured it might actually win quicker.

I had calculate the next few moves carefully but I managed to miss one important move.
Surprise
No surprises so far.
Of course I had seen it but I though I had a good reply.
If 35. Nh3 then we have a nice checkmate 35...Qxh3+; 36.Kg1 Qh1+; 36. Bxh1 Rxh1#;
I had calculated this far and believed I was going to win some material here.

Oopps!

And what a move!
Of cource Rxh5 is met with Rf8#;
And after 36..Qxh2+; 37.Qxh2; Rxh2+; 38. Kxh2 Nxg4+; 39. Kg3; Hxf2 black is left with a piece down.

How things haved turned!

My best bet. 
Now white should have continued 37. Bxe4! Qxf2;
After that white has the best chances.

The game seems to go in the same direction but there is a major difference.
Aggressive play till the very end.

Even now Bxe4 would have been better.
Black can not safe the exchange: 38. Ra2 Qe1+; 39.Ng1 Bxg2+; 40.Rxg2 Nf2+ etc.

If you think the game is even then you are mistaken.
White is in trouble because he need to defend both his kingsside and his queens side.
The poor knights dont have the leg be present on both sides of the board howoever.

If white has kept his bishop it would be a different game.
But as it is he is going to be overwhelmed.

White need to defend four things: his king pawns g4 and c4 and he need to stop balck a pawn.
Black can win four ways.
He can win by checkmating whites kings or he can march his a pawn to promotion.
Biut black can also gain pawn c4 in order to create an unstopppable pair of pawn on the a and b fil.
Finally black can win pawn g4 and then exchange all pieces to arrive and a winning pawn ending.

White has a hard time defending again all these threats.
Aggresive play yet again.
Nf1 is way too passive.

Another good move.
Originally I planned Qg3 but then realized I need to combine play on both ides of the board.
From here the Queen threatens white Kings threatens c4 and supports blacks a pawn.

Here comes the cavalery.!
White needs to play carefully or he will be in trouble.
Well played the Queen and Night should be able to stop the pawn with combined strength.

Ne1 seems better in order to bring the Knight to c2 to stop the a pawn.
Black easiest win would be Qe4+ and Qxc4 creating an unstoppable pair of pawns.

Another strong move ttacking Knight pawn c4 and supporting the a pawn.
The game is over because white can no longer defend against all these threats.
Nice last try but black has a simple response

And white resinged.

The end is forced 49.Kxh2 Qxd2+; 50. K~ Qb2;
And thee a-pawn is finally unstoppable.


What a game!
Here I present my very first tournament annotation. I hope you enjoy it.
I have never played anyone who has a responce ...e6? But it seems quite normal since lots of people play e5.
This move blocks white's LSB but supports the e4 pawn. Normal.
I usally play e5 after this move. Black is pushing some pressure onto white's e-pawn.
The e4 pawn is attacked twice and defended twice and after ...dxe4 dxe4 Nxe4 Nxe4 and white would win. So Nf6 might not have been the best move to play.
!? I personally wouldn't play this move I would play Bg5. But since black has just covered the e5 square d4 stops Nxe5 after e5. So I agree with both sides and think this is just a normal move.
White might play h3 (which is what I normally do) and chase the knight away.
!? I don't think this is the right time to play this move. If white is lucky and if black plays Bd7 then that would be the right time to capture.
Now the e-file is clear.
? This move blocks his LSB and if black plays Qe7 (which is not very likely after Qe7 Nxd5 wins a pawn) then both queens are pinned!
This is the correct way the answer the check. Next move might be O-O.

? This is another knight fork. Black has to capture with one of his knights and the queen puts threat on the g4-knight. But black can play Nxd4 and that threatens the white queen and the fork on c2 and if Qd2/Qd3 black would win by playing Nxe5!
!! Now black has multiple threats. Id Nxg4 tgeb Bxe2 and black wins. If Qxg4 Nxc2+ Kd1 Nxa1 wins. But if Qd3 Nxe5 wins a pawn (since after Qxd4 Nc6 and black ends up a pawn ahead.
At the moment this is the best thing that white could do defending black's threat. White is only a pawn down but this may cause problems in the endgame.
The black knight does not need to move as Bd6 is ok.
!! White's queen needs to move despratley. Bb5+ c6 Be2 Nf3+ check wins due to a discovered atack! If cxf3 Bxd4 wins!
! Black did not notice this move and now the position is equal nobody is winning at the moment. This move earns back a pawn because Nxd4 fails to Nf3 cxf3 Bxd4 winning a queen for a knight.
!? Black could take with Qxd4 easily but O-O shelters the king. As the queen is protected I think this move is not a blunder.
!? Getting ready to castle eh? Why not take with Qxd8? Should white play Qxd8 here or not?

? Carless white can now play Qxb7 winning a pawn. Even though black's two bishops are standing guard black will lose a pawn but after Qxb8 Rb8 Qe4 black wins a tempo while white wins a pawn and white clears the b-file.
?! Why not play Rb8. What use is this move? Qxc3 bxc3 and white is seven points ahead. Or is black aiming at f2? White can now play Qxc7.
Well that's no good because white has castled.
?? You'll see why a terrible mistake!
A rook skewer! After Qh4 Rxd8+ Bxd8 Qxa8 and white ends up a rook ahead. Is there anyway to stop the skewer?
Black thinks there's no way to stop it!
After the rook exchange white swoops in a piece ahead (rook and pawn of course)>

A bishop on the rim is dim? No no no well this bishop on the rim might be dim but if the c7 pawn was out of the way the bishop on the rim will not be dim. This rim on the dim thing only works for knight's not bishops. Anyway Qxa8 and white wins.
Now the bishop is pinned! But the bishop is not lost. c6 solves the problem (or c5).
?? He chose Nc6. This move blocks the white queen but there is one move that saves the day!
It is Bf3! Whatever black does he will lose a piece. Bd7 Bxc6 Bxc6 Qxd8+ wins. Nc4 Qxd8+ wins and Qb8  either Bxc6 or Qxc6 will win. (Qxc6 is probarly better.) unless black plays...

Nb8. Similarly like what I was talking to you about on move 16 this time the knight on the rim is dim because it can only move to four squares. Wait let's get off the game a minute and exterminate the pieces. Look whites DSB isn't even out yet as his a1 rook is in bed sleeping in the corner. What do you think about white's pawn structre and what do you think about black's pawn structre? At the moment which side has a more powerful attack? Answers please view on comments. Thank you.

!? What do you think about this move? 
Again answers on comments please. Is it intresting duibious blunder good move? Whatever.

Black is not defending very well and white is not attacking very well either. Now black has only got a few pieces left he needs to think about the way he plays. It is no good exchanging things. If you moved your queen white's Queen and bishop are blocked. At the moment black is three points down...

And now he is 6 points down. Is black's structre better? Worse? 
Is white's structre better? Worse?
!! But why?
What do you think about this move? Blunder or intresting Good or Bad Duibious or brillaint?
! If black plays Qxb2 (which he probarly will do) white wins by playing Qxd8+ and gets to be 8 points up. Let's see if black falls into the trap.
Uh-oh he does. Black is being very carless and now the game is lost for black. Luckily I've filmed it until white mated so you'll see how white managed to mate.
Black is losing. This move is the only move but is terrible.
A fork. Again another rare bishop fork. If you've looked in the annotion "The bishop pair" you would've seen a bishop fork there to. This is what I call a killer bishop fork!
And the game is definetly lost for black. The firing squad could obviously finish of the game.
But it's not so easy with so many pawns hanging around.
Getting the rook out.
On the rim again eh?
Game's nearly finished.

Checkmate!

The standard theory move here is the logical 4... Nf6. I don't know if the pawn double-step (that obviously is primarily done to keep the won pawn) here is sound as it kind of contradicts elementary opening rules namely that you shouldn't make too many pawn moves but instead develop your pieces quickly in the first stage of the game! This is especially essential when you accepted a gambit and therefore sacrificed development and initiative for material. Note that White already has two minor pieces developed one of them being a bishop sitting on a mighty long diagonal while Blacks fellows are all lazy in the back-camp so far. So my guess is that 4... Nf6 is better but I have to check out what the literature (Thomas Johansson - The Fascinating Reti Gambit) says about this line sometimes in future I don't own this book yet.
Challenging Blacks strong pawn centre threatening to win the pawn back.

Black does me a great favour and takes and now I can develop another minor piece in the next move. Note that the opponent only made pawn moves so far in the first five moves! Maybe 5... Nf6 would have been better leading to the possible continuation (not computer-checked yet): 6. dxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Rxd1 fxe4 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 10. Rd4 Bc5 11. Rc4 0-0 12. Nh3 with attacking chances for both sides.
Three pieces out versus zero. Blacks troops are still sleeping (or celebrating because of the won pawn).
Finally Black starts to develop.

A logical move since it prepares to castle queen-side (which is done most of the time in the Reti gambit -- the rook has an excellent place on the open d-file where the opponents queen is sitting) and it also threatens Bxf5 winning the pawn back and leaving Black with an ugly isolated pawn.

I remember that I kind of overlooked this move that attacks my queen. But well since the opponent moved his horse twice (breaking another opening rule) it also doesn't hurt for me to move my lady another time regarding development.
8. Qe3 would have been worth considering probably. I'm not sure what I was afraid of.
Develops another piece and pins my knight. It looks quite dangerous considering that queen and king are in the target line of his evil bishop but on the other hand it isn't too easy to exploit that.
White has almost finished development now only one piece needs to move to have nice position with connected rooks. Note that Black still needs at least four moves to accomplish the same.
Black is ready to castle king-side now and can place this knight on the strong square d5 where the pressure on my knight on c3 would increase.

The last missing piece gets out and challenges Blacks horse in the centre! At the time playing I avoided 10. Nf3 because if Black decided to take 10... Nxf3 gxf3 would have corrupted my pawn structure. But now I realise that the open g-file could have been very useful then considering Black probably castled king-side so maybe it would have been worth it! Anyway this way it was also not bad as we will see soon.

I guess it would have been wiser for Black to get his king to a safe place instead of helping White by freeing the queen from the pin comfortably and remove clutter from the powerful d-file empowering the rook. For example 10... 0-0 11. Bxf5 exf5 (... Nxf5? Qxd8 Rxd8 Rxd8+ winning the Exchange) 12. Qxd4 (or the more dangerous Nxd4) with an about equal position.
Still a pawn down White clearly enjoys the superior position now. The immediate threat is Bxf5 winning the pawn back and simultaneously attacking the queen.
Blacks queen decides to go out of the firing line.
Increasing the pressure on the half-open e-file and renewing the threat Bxf5.

Finally also Blacks king gets to a safe place -- at least for some time. Note that the idea of attacking the knight on c3 another time thinking that it can't move because the rook on e1 is exposed then and one could win the Exchange fails and leads to the loss of a piece: 12... Nd4 13. Nxd5 exd5 (the queen was attacked!) 14. Qxe7+ Bxe7 (now the bishop is back again and pinned) 15. Ba3! and the bishop is history.
Yes this still works the bishop waited a long time for his move! Material is even now again.
? Weakens my queen-side but loses the pair of bishops and throws away a piece that was quite active.
Okay this is what he had in mind -- unpinning the pawn on e6 with check trying to punish the bishop on f5 for using a simple tactical trick before. Good idea (that I overlooked) but it doesn't work.
Of course I have to keep the queen occupied. The at first sight more logical 15. Kb1?? would lose a piece 15... exf5.
Yes it costs a pawn. The queen looks dangerous here on this square so close to my king but in fact she isn't doing any harm at all.
I get the pawn back immediately in the centre.
My guess is that 16... Bxe6 trading the undeveloped bishop against my very active one and connecting rooks would have been stronger.
This way I decide to keep my strong piece.
I was glad at that point that my f2-pawn still exists.
All hail to the 7th rank! Threatens Rd7 (threatens mate on g7 in turn) the next move; if ... Nxd7?? then Qxg7#. Notice the huge impact the mighty bishop on b2 has in this position!
?? The final blunder that loses the game. Looks good as it defends the c7 and tries to get the queen back into the game. However it enables White to play a devastating...

... double attack! Note that Rd7 was probably still a playable option though one has to be careful not to leave the rook on e1 undefended that is eyed by Blacks queen now! However this way involving simple tactics seemed to be more safe and simple (and lust but not least fun!) to me.
A last straw hoping that I apply the wrong move order.
Of course 21. Rxa5?? Rxe7 would not have won anything.
I have no idea why he didn't take with the rook which seems to be much more natural to me compared to take a step back to the first rank with the horse leaving the bishop undefended.
White is a whole rook ahead now in material.

Small gifts will best maintain friendship ("Kleine Geschenke erhalten die Freunschaft" as we say in German). Black wisely decided to resign at this point. This is another game which shows how powerful and fun to play the Reti gambit can be. I'm pretty sure my opponent has lots of experience with the French defence and has played hundreds of games with it with the standard theory (following the normal 2. d4 d5) and if I played the let's say advance variation (3. e5) like I did in earlier times he probably would have played much stronger and killed me. However with this nice anti-French gambit I could nicely squeeze out an advantage right from the beginning and improve it more and more with quite simple moves. Feel free to comment!
My opponent uses a popular opening: King's pawn opening.
I reply almost mirroring my opponent.
? This does nothing at all.
I open up my bishop quickly.
He copies.
Now my queen I see that my opponent is not very strong after a4 I attempt a fast checkmate. If I was really being attacking and wanting to win quickly I would have played Qf6.
This does nothing again he should be opening up.
I threaten his pawn being protected by my own.
He walks past me.
I threaten again.
He protects.
I take.
And he takes back.
I threaten his pawn with pawn with my knight.
Blocking in then knight now I can take his pawn.
I take his pawn.
He retreats.
Now for the checkmate.
He could of played g3 (mate in two) but he decides there's no point.
Checkmate. Too easy.
The Sicilian Defence
This move takes us out of book.  3. d4 is the Marshall variation.  I'm mostly winging it on general principles.
Establishes an advanced (if somewhat difficult to defend) pawn and attacks the knight.
A coounter threat that weakens the e-pawn in the process.  A good move overall.

Black now has no developed pieces while White has three and an annoying advanced pawn.  This isn't a fantastic square for the bishop but it is better than where it started and is safe from pawn attack.

White has completed his development except for the queen.  His pieces are a little limited and Black is about to gain counterplay in the centre but White is in good shape if he can move his forces into action.

This looks like a weak move to me.  The queen wasn't doing much harm where it was and this opens up a diagonal on the rook that White can exploit to gain an aggressively-placed queen.  Nf6 would have also moved the queen on if Black really wanted that with better benefits.
The trade of queens would not be beneficial to White at this time. Instead the queen heads for the seventh rank from where it can be a pain in Black's side.
The White knight is off to join the attack via a4 to b6.  White also hopes to bring the bishop in and perhaps establish a rook at c1 for good measure
Attacking the isolated d-pawn.  Note that Black still has four pieces that have gone nowhere.

Rfd1 might have been better retaining Rac1 for later.  White could also have played Bb6 to threaten Qd8# but Bd7/Be6 and f6 defend against it and the knight can no longer go to b6 himself (whereas the bishop will be equally effective at a5).

I don't know what the queen is doing here.  It's on a locked-up diagonal and doesn't attack any of the essential squares.  The one thing it would do is defend d8 after Nd5.  Nd5 now works better attacking the queen and either breaking up the attack or forcing it to redirect by taking b6 away from the knight.
The bishop develops to allow the rook to operate along the back rank defending against the attacks.  Again Nd5 was better.

Directly attacking the rook.  White should now win at minimum two pawns and a battered Black queenside (19. ... Nd5 20. Qxb7 Rd8 21. Qxa6) and if Black tries to preserve the rook and with 19. ... Rd8 20 Nd7 wins the queen while 19. ... Ra7 collapses to the same move.

Attacking the queen and re-establishing the queen-bishop diagonal.  The best defence is probably Qxf2+ continuing Rxf2 f6 but even with best play White is just too far ahead (I easily beat full-strength Shredder after 20. Nd7).
Of the moves that do nothing to defend against the attack this is perhaps the best.

Note that the Black king is almost totally hemmed in by his own pieces.  Only one Black piece ever made it into the White half of the board.  Black's failure to develop proved costly as White was able to smother him.
Most common moves as far as I'm concerned.

This is the Center Game an opening that was another opening said to have been lost in the shadows of the Ruy Lopez. I will make sure that it comes back alive in this game if I can win (not that it matters if I win).
Throw this move into the waste-bucket! 2...exd4 is significantly better.
Not the best effort but still sufficient enough to solid development.

Here's a poem: If a Knight's on the rim it's future is grim; it's chances of survival are very slim. My advice: don't develop the Knight on the edge when the Queen is out; wait for the Queen to move away from the Knight's square then move the Knight. Right now I can win a point but I think that it is too risky at this moment.
I continue my development therefore.
No problem because of 5.Nc3. The problem is that I might not want to unpin the Kinght until my King is castled.
Certainly not the best. However this doesn't mean that the Knight cannot develop. How I wish that I found d5 now?
Well I guess I could do that.
I believe that Black thinks that if I can win a pawn he can win one when he wants.
Now would be a good time to create space for my pieces.
?! This move makes Black's Queen look absolutely ridiculous on it's spot. Perhaps Qe6 before castling could make things look better for Black.
Unreasonable. 8.Bc4 is preferred.
This move can be bothersome. If I played Bc4 then he played this move it will be an absolute blunder! Better was 8...Qe6.
So far so good...temporary.
I knew Black was going for 10...Nxe5. Therefore I played this move. I am influenced to watch out for LS weaknesses.
A disasterous blunder! Better was the simple 10...d6.
Black should just play 11...Kh8.
This move is a careless move that says"I already played d6 and now I'll wait for that puny Queen to come after me." Of course that was off the hook compared to Kh8 losing less points.
Good-bye Knight.
Only best move.

This event actually tested to see if in this position Black can Castle without taking risks? As I evaluated"For every move there are advantages and disadvantages. If they are equal then it is an okay move. If a move is a bit more of a disadvantage then it is an inaccurate move. If there are more diadvantages then it is a mistake. If there is only one advantage (which applies only if the opponent makes the one ridiculous move) then it is a blunder. However if there are more advantages than disadvantages then it'll likely be a definite good move.  In that case think about your moves and their purposes and think of them as your advantages. Then look at your opponents' pieces and decide if he has moves to play against you and put those as the disadvantages. Analyze then find out for yourself if what you want to move will be a good move or not.
I might want to Castle now to counterattack this move.
Well maybe I should have Castled before playing this move but I think it works.
I think Black is experimenting with my position (not a good idea at all).
Looks like Queenside Castling is a bit safer.
15...Rf7 looks better due to my next move.
! This move pins the pawn to 2 targets and makes 16...Rf7 Black's only move!
What else could Black play? Absolutely nothing!
18.Rae1 looks good for White. Unfortunately for Black the pawn is still pinned indirectly to his Rook. Developing his LSB is probably his only chance...
...It looks like my King is better off in the corner.
Black will want to do the same too.
I don't know why Black wants to hinder his Queenside development but this move makes 19.Ne4 seem winning for White.
? What does this accomplish? Better was 19.Nf3 Ne4 and a variety of other moves.
I don't really like this move either.

? What was Black thinking sitting in the open unsafe letting my Quenn mercilessly destroy four more points? I don't know what other move Black had to get away from what is coming up but this is definitely not his best move.
Let the King chase commence. Of course I have to think it out but I think I play some unthoughtful moves.
There's one place Black is eyeing at to take shelter in: the Queenside.
24.f6+ looks fine with the exception of making Black's Queenside seem like a great home for Black's King.
Don't worry about your Rook Black. I'll make sure I won't capture it (maybe; it depends on what I need to do which depends on where Black moves).
Threatening 26.Ng5+
Change of plans...
Black's Queenside after his most recent move is used uselessly by the LSB trying to gain something out of this lost game. This means that Black has no other chances of being safe again forever.
Now I'll make sure that Black has no chance of turning the tides.
These next moves are forced I think.
This move wasn't forced but moving to my Queenside is equally dangerous.
Only move gets Black checkmated.
There's the "only move". Here comes the checkmate.

Instead of the losing move 25...Bb7 how about if Black played 25...Bd7 to leave an escape square for his King and make that "escape square" a home for then? Well even if he did this same position is likely to occur except that I get to take the Rook after Black's move. This is a great example of how to lose an escape square in King chases. Make sure to keep an eye out for possible escape squares and make sure that if you can make one and use it in time you use it wisely. However every lesson we learn about chess is based on the question "Are you thinking about where you move and use your time wisely or are you making a bunch of moves that are saying 'I hope you do this'?" If you're admitting that you made a bunch of random moves (referring to the question above) you are playing a chess coach's most disliked game of Hope Chess. I have to admit it is the most miserable excruciatingly painful and hopeless game anyone ever plays. To close this up please avoid playing Hope Chess.

The start of the game proper.  White is supporting the central e-pawn and activating the dsb although the computer considers this a weak move.  Castling and taking the bishop are far and away the most popular options and seem to do well for White.
Black pushes the bishop to a decision.
Capturing towards the centre.
The point of 3. ... g6 was to allow this move.  Black gains decent control of one of the long diagonals.
7. ... e6 was obviously intending d5 to follow.  Establishing the rook at e1 makes opening up the centre less palatable for Black.

Not considered a mistake or inaccuracy by the computer but it does shift the evaluation down by about 1/3 of a pawn.  Black's aim is to open up for castling without blocking the bishop at g7.  The knight has more opportunity to be useful from here than from h6.
Seals off the bishop at g7 and is well supported here.  Also creates issues for the lsb developing through the e6 pawn.
Black attempts to break the deadlock.  The computer takes another third of a pawn here leaving Black at -1.
An unnecessary further reinforcing of the pawn.  White can instead win a pawn here with exd6 followed by Nc3.
Black changes plans and opts to try undoubling his pawns.  His bishops are still in trouble and dxe5 was probably better.
An uncertain move for me.  It doesn't seem to have much purpose.
Black tidies the king away in the interim.
Eyeing the vulnerable c5 pawn.

Bad.  Black has designs on winning a piece and even if he doesn't he still claims a small pawn wedge in the middle of the board.  But White can severly cramp his style in a line that according to the computer leaves White ahead two pawns.  It prefers 14. ... Bd7 to deter that line.
! The computer's best move that leaves White at +2.

Not sure about this move.  Black is under pressure and the pawn at c5 is lost and he wants to preserve the queen rather than entice the enemy into attempting the exchange and offer protection to the d-pawn.  The computer prefers Qc6 but this scores about the same.
Protecting the d4 pawn.
Presumably intending to join the fight with Rc4.  The computer prefers to attack the queen with Bg5.
Moves the bishop out of the White queen's line of fire.  Can also now trade with the knight for a weakened castle.

The only place from which the bishop won't immediately be moved on again and it allows the bishop to swing over to the queenside.  However exf6 would have opened up the e-file for White's well-placed rook and would have been better.

An attack on the queen that seems poorly planned as the queen can just move away.  There aren't any active squares the queen can safely move to but the queen can trade itself or move to safety and force the rook to either shuffle home or pointlessly trade down.
The White queen chooses inactivity over death.
The pawn is only temporary.  Better was Bxf3 opening up the castle by brute force.  The computer has hated the last four moves and now regards the position as +0.04 for Black.
After the rook trade White tries an attack that can't really go anywhere.
!  Ignoring the threat to his rook Black attacks the knight and the castle.
Protecting the queen from the attack but hemming it in at the same time.  Better would have been to move the queen.

A seemingly sensible idea taking the bishop away from danger (though what it's doing where it is I can't really say).  Better was Nh4 which wins at the computer has winning heavily after gxf3 Nxf3+ Kf1 Nxf1 Kxf1.  It's tough for me to see what to do after 24. ... Nh4 25. g3.

The computer prefers to play 25. ... Qc3 threateing a queen trade with a dangerous passed pawn being shepherded through by the bishops or else using the bishops to pick up the loose queenside pawns.  I think of this option as more conservative.
A questionable decision in my opinion.  The knight was valuable - I don't think White should be exchanging down without a clear advantage.

exd5 was also possible.  Using the Queen results in losing a queenside pawn instead of a central one (probably not good given White's existing queenside pawn advantage) and gives White a possible mating attack with Nh4.
Cuts out that attack Black was planning but allows the knight to make a mess by advancing via e3 and c2.
Preserving the a-pawn and attacking White's b-pawn and ultimately the queen.

The idea is to threaten the rook and pick up a pawn.  But 29. Rb1 will severely lock down the position.  The computer rates the position as almost dead even now instead of solidly winning for Black.  Activating the king with Kf7 was better.
Black gets his edge back as this unsupported attack must fade out.
Adding support to the attack but the knight/pawns combo is holding the position.
Creates a passed pawn in the middle.

The computer doesn't like this but the intent is clear - Black wants to emphasise the passed pawn by reducing material and is confident his bishop and knight can contain the rook and get the pawn home.
Putting the pawn in the bishop's protection.  Threats to the bishop or the a pawn can be met with a4 at will.
The only good move.  Anything else and White will lose his rook and be in massive trouble.
The knight must reach the fight zone but is unable to do so via the kingside.  It will be a long journey however.
A change of approach for White who now gives check for not much reason.
The Black king is on his way to the pawn.  The check has done nothing to hinder him.
Frees the rook from the job of guarding the pawn against promotion.  It does however give the Black king access to e3 which will prove vital.
??  The game is done as White can no longer prevent the pawn from promoting without losing his rook.
41. Rd4 41. Re3 and 41. Rc4 are the only options that prevent Nc3# and they all lose the rook (Rc4 swaps it for the knight).  White resigns as he is lost.
Interesting choice here for black.  It later becomes obvious to me that I have a better grasp of the pawn game than fermoncada does but at least early on he uses them forcefully.
Ye olde knight pin.  I'm a fan.
Interesting choice by black to trade knight for bishop here after opening the board up by taking pawns.  I wondered what he was up to.
Complete violation of the Knights-Before-Bishops rule of thumb.  I would've done Nc6.  I expected his bishop to come out to f6 and attack the center but I think he was just making room to castle.
I'm feeling pretty comfy with the center at this point.
Why bring the bishop out if you're just going to block it in??  I don't get this move at all except in the "castle ASAP" idea.
I'm feeling a little aggressive here.  Probably not the best idea since it'll let his black bishop out now that I think about it.

And out comes my queen.  I considered the pawn take but I figured the queen up here was gonna be a thorn in his side.  Now I'm threatening b7 and he's got to watch out for d6 and f7.  And thanks to his earlier bishop trade and pawn trade he's got nothing to scare her away with.
Counter-attack by threatening b2.  Nice move.  I consider castling queenside but figured I could just as easily counter with...
I don't get this trade. Why come here?  I admit my queen is in a better position than his but hell the board opens up more and I have both bishops.  Plus I get to mess up his pawn structure.
The best part of that queen trade for me is this position.  I have for now completely shut down his queenside pawns.  He's got nothing he can do there for a while.

I spent a lot of time analyzing this position.  It was clear that black intended knight to b4 to c2 for a fork.  The problem was that anything that prevented the fork was at risk of walking into a trap.  I considered 15. Bd2 for some time but then the knight could go to d3 and cause trouble.  Any attempt to stop the fork by using the a1 rook would hang the a2 pawn and allow black's rook to move to b8 and undermine the pawn structure.  It was a complicated decision to castle but in the end I decided I could neutralize both the fork and the problem of Nd3.
As expected.  Black probably figured it was win/win - if the a1 rook moves the a2 pawn hangs.  If not Nc2 can challenge it while keeping the f-rook locked down.
This move was intended to open up the d file for my rook and prevent d5 later.
I figured black wouldn't be able to resist Nd3 here attacking the unprotected bishop.  Nc2 was suicide by this point.

It's a careful dance.  I want to keep the black knight as locked down as possible.  This move makes black's only knight move to f4 that accomplishes little.  Meanwhile he's blocking the d file and keeping black's rooks from claiming it.  I'm planning Bxc6 to win the pawn.

Black either anticipated Bxc6 and wanted to move the rook out of danger early or expected 19. Be2 or Be4 which would threaten the knight.  I honestly don't like those moves because they just push black's knight away.
Free pawn and now black's f8 rook is locked down.

Black moves his knight out freeing up the d file for his rook and leaving it ready to defend the bishop at e7 if need be.  A good move but he's forgotten that the knight was the only thing keeping me off the e1 squarerook...

Simple and direct.  I'm expecting Ng6 here.  I would then respond with bringing the a1 rook into play on d1 and challenging black's control of that file.  The queenside pawns are also waiting to become a nice battering ram that will lock down black's rooks.  I'm feeling pretty good about this position.
Big blunder.  Forgetting the knight completely black hangs his rook.
I win the exchange and now have the d-file all to myself.
I'm clearly winning here but need to be cautious.  I see Rd7 in my future and then a peaceful walk up the a or b files to queen.
He's got plans for his bishop I see.  This lets it move without risking back-rank mate and his knight can enter the battle on either side from here.  Solid move.
Time to harass that a-pawn.
Obvious move.  a5 would fall to the bishop and Ra8 loses his bishop.
Just making sure he comes up no farther.
He's offering a bishop trade.  I'm up material so hell yes.  He thinks he's saving his a-pawn.  He's wrong.
I want that a-pawn.
Interesting move this one.  I really did not see what he had planned and paid for it later.
Here's an interesting position.  He's wanting my b3 pawn for his f6 one.  I thought I could stop him by pinning the knight to his rook.  Big mistake.
Oops.  I give back the exchange I won before.  I'm still up in pawns and still have a much better position afterwards but ouch this hurts.
To state the obvious Kh1...Rxd1#.  This is forced.
I saw where this was going.  He wanted to harass my kingside pawns now.  I was gonna have to shut that down quick.
He's stopping g4 for now.  If I do it it'll free his rook up in exchange for nothing.
One advantage of my screwup is that his rook is stuck behind my lines for now and mine is out and about.

And here's where I make a second mistake though this one's not nearly as bad.  From here Rf5 is completely dominating.  He gets one of my pawns and I get one of his.  I can then pretty confidently force a rook trade and win the king&pawn endgame.  Instead I defend which extends the game significantly.

The reason I made this mistake is because I saw an interesting rook dance forming here and was intrigued by it 'cause I rarely get to play this rook-v-rook endgame.  I figured I could force his rook into stagnation on the a-file and I was right.
He sees it coming and starts trying to activate his king.
It won't work however.  His king can't make it in time even if my rook lets him.
I'm guessing he was hoping I'd dodge to d3 or d1 to try and attack his rook which would've set said rook loose on my pawns.  Fat chance.
and just like that all my pawns are covered AND his kingside play is shut down.  He has nothing now but to try and hold for a draw.
He seems to go back to plan A: kill the a-pawn.  This was a small mistake.  The a-pawn is safe no matter what as you'll see.
He can threaten my rook by going to c7 but then I queen.  His only chance is to prevent that with his rook at the same time.

which he tries.  But here's where the king's presence at d7 helps me.  If he'd been at d8 my plan still would have worked I think with Rb8+...Kc7 a8=Q...Rxa8 Rxa8 and I've won the rook.  It's mop-up afterwards.  But this way I lock his rook down and start a kingside attack.  Slower to be sure but I've pretty much won the game by this point.
Rb8+...Kc7 a8=Q would've traded rook for pawn and I missed that.  I'd found a way to win and didn't want to deviate even though this would've won faster.  It's a bad habit I'm working on.

Since I missed winning the rook I follow my plan.  Taking out the f7 pawn means the kingside is almost clear.  Trying to bring up the f2 pawn would be a mistake - his king is too active.  I have other plans.
From here on out all he can do is pray I blunder.
Why g4?  Well I force him to remove his last pawn that can do anything or let me pass at full throttle.  The sad thing is that even now I could've done Rf8+...Ke7 a8=Q and he loses his rook.
So now I have the passed g-pawn the a-pawn and the f-pawn.  That's WAY too much for him to defend.
My God.  Looking back on this game there were so many opportunities to win his rook.  In the end he had to GIVE it to me.
He's defending the g-pawn.  It won't help but damn it.  I STILL had Rb8+.

I basically have free run of the board with my king.  Do I wander over and take his c pawn then walk up the c file?  Do I escort my g-pawn up to queen?  It's all up to me.  and I STILL fail to see Rb8+.

From here on out I'll just assume you all know how much of an idiot I am for not just winning his rook.

This move was key believe it or not.  Kf4 seems a better move at first glance but once you see Rxf2+ you see he can harass my king all the way to the bank.
Clever move here.  He's defending the queening mate.  Won't help but credit where it's due.  fermoncada fought hard the entire match.
Heck yes I'll take that rook.  From here it's a game of choose-how-I'll-mate-you.  Took me long enough to win that rook though.  Sheesh.
At this point we are well into my endgame comfort zone.  I've planned out every possible move.
Well played fermoncada.
The King's Pawn Opening.
I respond with the "cornerstone" of the Sicilian Defense.
? This is a blunder.  In this position he is trying to play the Open Sicilian so 2.Nf3 would have been his best move.
I decided to continue with this defense.
? This is a mistake.  Even though his LSB is not jammed it is not in a good spot.  In this position I will trap his LSB later in the game.

? I made this move to trap his LSB as soon as I could but this is not the proper continuation of the Sicilian Defense.  Therefore 3...a6 would have been my best move.  If however 1.e4c5 2.Nf3d6 3.d4 then 3...cxd4 would be best.
I do not know why he chose this candidate.
I made this move to trap his LSB as I had mentioned earlier.
Therefore he is forced to retreat his bishop.

I chose this candidate because I wanted to exchange his bishop for one of my pawns.  That way I would be two points ahead.  In this position I actually thought that I was going to win his LSB but I was wrong.  That will be explained shortly.
This was the first move that I had overlooked but it was not a blunder because this is a "nuisance check".  However I will overlook moves and it will get ugly later in the game.

I made this move because I figured that he would exchange his bishop for my knight with 7.Bxc6+bxc6. The usual King's Pawn opening.  I am used to seeing this because 1.e4 is also my favorite opening.

This is the "cornerstone" of the Sicilian Defense and I like it better then the King's Pawn Game.  First it prevents some of white's pieces from breaking through.  Second it is more aggressive then 1...e5.  In other words the Siclian Defense is more of an attack then a defense.  However the King's Pawn Game is more of a defense then an attack.  Most importantly white cannot get away with violating Opening General Principles if 1...c5 is played.  As Bobby Fisher would say "Best by Test" but I do not know if that statement applies to opening principles.

?  This is his first blunder.  In this position he is trying to get a "Scholars Mate" but I am not going to let him mate me in four moves.  In addition he has violated an opening principle because this does not give him a tactical advantage.  Therefore he is supposed to develop his knight before the bishop.  To top it off the game is unofficially lost.  This was not his loosing blunder but I will be as aggressive as I can.  In other words I will show no mercy when he makes more blunders.  I generally defeat my opponents with their own mistakes but that is especially true in this game.  That is because I feel insulted when people attempt this dirty trick especially a team game even though I am not angry.  This attitude however is a blunder as it causes stubbornness and inflexibility.  On the other hand it does not cost me in this game.

! At this point I decide to transpose the Sicilian Defense into the French Defense as a result of his last move.  This is the proper response to an attempted "Four Move Trick" because it reduces the bishops diagonal.  In addition I am not going to show amnesty as I had mentioned earlier.

However this is also a blunder and another violation of Opening General Principles.  That is because you are not supposed to bring the queen out early and this mistake will cause him problems later in the game.

On the other hand this was not my worst move because he will also loose a bishop.  As a result the score will be even when 6.Bxd7+ Nbxd7 are played.

Normally I play 6...Nc6 the Panno Variation; but I been reading some Joe Gallagher.  Gallagher felt that the type of players that played the Fianchetto Variation liked to feel in control and the way get them out of their comfort zone was to create chaos on the board and disrupt the flow of their games.  So I play ...Ndb7 hoping to be able to transpose into the Gallagher Variation.
Played with the idea of 10. Bd2 c5 making it difficult for White to get his thematic queenside play.
What is this? White is playing for f4.  I decided it was time to switch plans and go for the traditional KID kingside attack by Black.

Played with some regret.  Visually I didn't like my position but I have a supported passed pawn and White's h4-Knight is on the rim and no easy way back into the game.  I remembered Larsen once summing up a position as both sides stand badly.  That seemed to apply here.
Here Fritz recommends 13...Nc5.  During the game I missed the fact that White can't play 14.b4?.
Better is Fritz's suggestion of 14...c5.
I was definitely wishing I had played the Panno at this point.
Once again 16...c5 could be played.
Fritz suggests 18...b5
My pieces are starting to uncoil White's h4 knight is still a longways from getting back into the game and my Kingside action is starting to take shape.  I was starting to feel better about things.
?! Fritz recommends 20.Bf2
Normally Black dislikes parting with his ds Bishop but I wanted to get my f7 rook to g7 without having to worry about a White bishop on the long diagonal.
?! stronger is 21...Qf6.  Black's move here helps solve White's h4-knight problem.
?! better was 22.Nhxf5 which would have kept White in the game.
Here White resigned.  I felt somewhat prematurely.  Black certainly has a large advantage but there is a ways to go.
So far very common moves from both sides.
Gameknot database calls this 'open (Tarrash) defense'.
Most common reply it seems
gives a pawn-advantage but...
...now the knight is pinned
of course it needs to be protected. but this actually pins the other knight too ;-).

!?... most common here seems to be Nxd4. This position was new to me though so I consulted the gameknot DB and that move seemed to have a high success rate (yes this was my main motivation to play this move you can blame me on that :-P )
The most played move but gameknot analyzer considers this as 'inaccuracy' and suggests Qd6 instead.

putting pressure on his knight on c6. 
After a possible 9. ...fxg5 10. Nxc6 would give me the knight and threaten the queen (10. ... bxc6? 11. Bxc6+ would let me take the rook and I would still be treatening f3)
'semi-pins' my knight.
Still I decided to keep on playing offensive... (chess should be fun right? ;-) )

That's why I said 'semi-pinned'. At this position I started to realize that I have underestimated the difficulty of this position. Both sides have possible attacks but one single wrong move on each side might lead to a losing position.
Not sure if Kh1 would have been the better choice

I expected this move somehow. now my knight is pinned too if I move it away black can simply play Qxa4. This position made me think a very long time I probably have spent 1 hour trying out a lot of different possible next moves...

After thinking for this long I finally decided to make this move. Since black's knight is still pinned he can't just take my knight. Also it treatened to win black's queen by doing Ne5 next move (since the Bishop on a4 was protected now). Because of that black couldn't play fxg5 or Bxe1 in next move as this would have let me capture the queen.

?? Now this move surprised me I was simply expecting bxc6. It really seems to be a blunder as the gameknot analyzer changes the rating from +0.55 to +5.69 for white. Amusingly I wasn't aware of that at this point I still thought the position is quite equal.

Now have a closer look at this position I just find it too nice ;-). It seems that 4 of my pieces (both knights and both bishops) are 'en prise'. Furthermore my rook still could be taken with black's Bishop so black actually had 5 possible captures at this point ;-). Of course at the current position I had captured 2 knights while black only had 2 pawns.

?!. And still none of pieces were captured. I understand that black wanted to bring in more pieces and that he wanted to bring his king in safety. Of course I was threatening something like Nxf6+ for winning the queen but I was actually expecting either Qxc6 dxe4 or probably Bxe1. 
At this position I started to realize I really seem to have an advantage... but still I didn't see a clear path to a fast win... I just felt this position has a lot of potential and I started to think very long about my next move again...
?!... After the long thought I just couldn't resist this one. After 14. ... Qxe7 follows 15. Nxf6+ which would win the queen (... Qxf6 16. Bxf6 or ...Kh8 16. Rxe7).
that avoids the queen being captured still leaving 4 (or 5) of my pices 'en prise' but...

now I could simply capture the bishop so instead of 5 pieces being attacked there now only were the 2 bishops left (as the knight on e7 was protected by the rook now). So at this point my advantage was for sure now ;-). +4 in material after the capture of a bishop.
was expecting c6 here saving the pawn
I simply accepted the exchange because I was +5 in material... each exchanged pieces makes the win easier in such a position I think
gameknot analyzer doesn't like this move and suggests Rad1 instead. But didn't change much anyway.
And black resigned

Here white's a pawn has to be stationary. White's other pawns (files b-f) need to capture a combined total of 15 black pieces (black's entire army except the king) so they cannot push either. That leaves either the g or h pawn or a knight as the first move of this proof.
The idea is to promote black's g and h pawns using white's own g and h pawns as a sacrifice.

Getting the knight out of the way of the promotions; 3 Rh3 followed by 4 Re3 gets the king's rook out of the way as well. The bishop needs to stay on f1 to prevent the newly promoted queens from delivering check.
I decided to promote black's f-pawn as well. However the queen on g1 needs to get out of the way.
An alternative is 13 ... Qh2.
Now putting these queens in place for the later capture. A non-promoted black pawn cannot move three files toward the queen side without taking three of white's pieces so a promotion had to occur.
Now the e and d pawns can be pushed to their capture squares.
Now the queen has to be moved back again else the d pawn cannot progress.
The d and e files are now ready to be captured.
Now's the right time to get white's first capture.
The idea is to get black's army clumped up into the a3-e3-a6 triangle. One of these a bishop was already taken.
Knight's in place!
Queen can go here to take knight bishop and queen on b1-d1.
King stays here for the rest of the proof.
Now to offer to the queen.
I need a queen not the pawn on a7 so that come the puzzle board the a7 piece can still move.
Now the capture spree.
And this is the perfect parity for the puzzle board.
And now to enact the solution...
...checkmate! Is there a way to optimize this proof? I know this is not the optimum yet I also know that it's hard to fully optimize this proof.

Hello I would like to annotate an enjoyable game that I recently played here on Gameknot. There are quite a few mistakes in the game but I have tried to explain in a way that lower rated players can learn something.

c5 the Sicilian defence. e4 is perhaps the most common opening move so it is essential to learn a good response to it. I prefer to play c5 rather than e5 because it is more aggressive and gives black a more open game.
d6 is the most common move here by black but Nc6 is absolutely playable. The idea is to challenge the d4 square.

Bc4 is not a move I have seen often. The gameknot database suggests that it is slightly inferior to the more common move of d4 (initiating the pawn exchange by black). Bb5 and Nc3 also yield better results for white overall.
Planning to play d5 driving back whites LSB gaining tempo space and control of the centre.
Developing the knight to a good square and preventing d5 for the moment.
Developing the knight to a good square and preparing again to play d5.
Activating the DSB and providing support.
Finally I get to play d5 attacking whites bishop.
Pawn exchange.

Retreat and loss of tempo. At this point I lose access to the GK database it shows that black has a reasonable advantage already presumably due to blacks stronger central control and small space advantage.

I think this is a mistake as it allows white to capture the pawn on d5. Without access the the DB and having just got back from several months hitch hiking in West Africa where chess is almost unheard of I am a bit rusty. Better moves would have been Be7 or Bg4.
Both sides get their king off the dangerous open e file.

Stops any ideas of pinning whites knight with Bg4 but opens up other possibilities such as a sacrifice on h3. I think perhaps this move was a bit slow at this stage with Bg5 or Nxd5 being better alternatives.
Threatens the N and prevents Nxd5 but whites bishop now has a strong diagonal aiming at my king!
I think Nb5 is slightly better but I am not sure.
Three enemy pieces can land on g5 so I decide to secure it.
Contesting the crucial open e file. I later realised this to be a mistake. Nxe4 dxe4 then Re8 is a much better alternative as will be explained.

c3?? Both players missed the significance of Nxf6+. The Queen cannot recapture on f6 because it would leave the rook on e8 attacked and undefended. After 12. Nxf6+ gxf6 13. Rxe8+ Qxe8 14. Bxh6 giving white a huge advantage.
The possibility of Nxf6+ is still there.
The rook on e8 now has another defender making Nxf6 a less serious threat.
Too late!
Eyeing up the black Queen but white cannot open the diagonal until the bishop on b2 is defended.
I decided to exchange here because if white recaptures with the Queen I can win the d pawn and recapturing with the Knight weakens whites position.
Munch.
c4! Defends my annoying bishop on d3 attacks whites bishop and advances a Queenside pawn where I now have a majority.
Ba5 is better.
Forces the Queen to d1 where defensive possibilities are more limited.

Secures the bishop and takes control of the open file. It is important to note that the rook is also defended here. Blacks pieces are now working together well. White has a cramped position his bishop on b2 is almost useless and it will be a few moves until his rook can have an influence on the game.
Bxd3? White tries to trade off the annoying piece but it allows the pawn on c4 to become passed and dangerously close to promotion.
Rb1? g3 Bc7 Nd2 may have offered better resistance.
